      <p>Unison is a programming language built around <a href="/docs/the-big-idea/">one big idea</a>: let's identify a definition by its actual contents, <strong>not</strong> just by the same name that also referred to its older version. Unison code lives in a database called your "codebase". The human-friendly names are there too, but they're just for looks, when your code is rendered on the fly as text <em>when</em> you're reading or editing it.</p>
      <p>Our ecosystem leverages this core idea from the ground up. Some benefits: we never compile the same code twice; many versioning conflicts‚Ä¶ aren't; and we're able to build sophisticated self-deploying distributed systems within a single strongly-typed program.</p>
